The famous Iris database, first used by Sir R.A. Fisher. The dataset is taken
from Fisher's paper. Note that it's the same as in R, but not as in the UCI
Machine Learning Repository, which has two wrong data points.

This is perhaps the best known database to be found in the
pattern recognition literature.  Fisher's paper is a classic in the field and
is referenced frequently to this day.  (See Duda & Hart, for example.)  The
data set contains 3 classes of 50 instances each, where each class refers to a
type of iris plant.  One class is linearly separable from the other 2; the
latter are NOT linearly separable from each other.

.. dropdown:: References

    Mathematical Statistics" (John Wiley, NY, 1950).
  - Duda, R.O., & Hart, P.E. (1973) Pattern Classification and Scene Analysis.
    (Q327.D83) John Wiley & Sons.  ISBN 0-471-22361-1.  See page 218.

Answer¶

The pairplot shows that Iris Setosa (0) is completely separated from the other species using petal length and width. Iris Versicolor (1) and Virginica (2) overlap more, especially when looking only at sepal measurements. The best separation is seen in petal length vs petal width, where Virginica has the largest values, Versicolor is in the middle, and Setosa has the smallest. This means that petal measurements are the most informative features for distinguishing species.

Singular value decomposition factorizes matrix
$X \in mxn$
into
$X = U \, * \, \sum \, * \, V^T$
Where:

  • $U \in m×m$ that is called the left singular vectors where each columns is a orthonormal eigenvectors of $XX^T$
  • the diagonal matrix Σ with entries single entries $\in \mathbb{R}$ that are the non-negative singular values of X
  • and the right singular vectors in Matrix $V \in n×n$ where the columns are the set of orthonormal eigenvectors of $X^TX$

The SVD algorithm from the numpy package can calculate this quite efficiently

# Using 4 numeric feature columns
feature_cols = iris.feature_names             

# Standardize (zero mean, unit variance) for SVD/PCA
X_std = StandardScaler().fit_transform(X4)

# SVD on standardized 4-feature matrix
U, S, VT = np.linalg.svd(X_std, full_matrices=False)
S2 = S**2
total = S2.sum()
ratio = S2 / total
cum = np.cumsum(ratio)

print("Explained variance ratio (4 comps):", ratio)
print("Sum of S^2:", total)
print(f"Two PCs total: {cum[1]*100:.2f}%")

plt.figure()
plt.plot(range(1, len(cum)+1), cum, marker='o')
plt.xticks(range(1, len(cum)+1))
plt.xlabel("Number of components")
plt.ylabel("Cumulative explained variance")
plt.title("Cumulative explained variance (SVD on standardized 4 features)")
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

Explained variance ratio (4 comps): [0.72962445 0.22850762 0.03668922 0.00517871]
Sum of S^2: 600.0000000000001
Two PCs total: 95.81%

Answer¶

The Iris dataset is highly compressible: The SVD results show that the sum of squared singular values is 600, representing the total variance. The first principal component PC1 explains ~73% of the variance, and the second PC2 ~23%. Together, the first two components capture ~95.8% of the dataset’s variance.

Instead of 4 features, we can use just 2 principal components and still keep ~96% of the information.

  • This is why PCA/SVD are useful: we can simplify the data without losing much structure.
  • The last two components (PC3, PC4) don’t matter much; they carry very little variance.

This means we can reduce the data from 4D to 2D with very little loss of information. Components 3 and 4 add almost nothing, which confirms that 2D is enough for analysis and visualization.

Answer¶

In the raw feature space (sepal length vs sepal width), the species overlap heavily, and it is difficult to distinguish Versicolor from Virginica.

In the SVD space (first two components), Setosa is clearly separated, and Versicolor vs Virginica are more spread out. This shows that dimensionality reduction captures the directions of maximum variation and helps separate classes better than using raw features.

Illustration of SVD¶

To better understand the effect of SVD we will look at a simplified dataset and normalize the data. Then we will simplify and illustrate the calculation of the projection onto the axis we will rotate the axis system and use the y-value as perpendicular projection $z_i$ in formula 12.5 or figure 12.2 in the book.

Answer¶

After filtering to Versicolor and Virginica and normalizing petal length and width, we see two overlapping but distinct groups.

Virginica flowers generally have larger petal dimensions, while Versicolor flowers are smaller.

Normalization ensures both features contribute equally, and the data is centered at (0,0). This prepares the dataset for the next step, where SVD will rotate the axes to maximize separation between the two classes.

Task - rotation¶

Create a composite figure with a few plots in each of which you rotate the axis by an angle $\alpha$. The coordinates can be understood as:
x=r cos($\alpha$) and y=r sin($\alpha$)
So the rotation of around the center we can express as:
$$ \begin{bmatrix} x' \\ y' \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} cos(\alpha) & sin(\alpha) \\-sin(\alpha) & cos(\alpha)\end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix}$$

We’ll rotate the (normalized) 2-D petal data by an angle α and see which angle makes the perpendicular residual (the y′ values) as small as possible. That “best” angle is the same direction SVD/PCA would pick for the first principal component.

Task¶

The y-value of each point corresponds to the $z_i$ value or the value that is not explained by the vector we assume here that for the perfect vector the euclidian distance is the same as the y-value.
The sum of the squared values corresponds to the variance that is not explained by the vector and that is to be minimized. The x-values (after rotation) correspond to the value of the variance that is explained by the first independent vector. For an $\alpha$ from 0 to 360 plot the sum of the squared y-values against the angle. With matplotlib this can e.g. be achieved with:

    fig, ax = plt.subplots(subplot_kw={'projection': 'polar'})
    ax.plot(alpha, r)
In [29]:
# Sweep angles from 0..360 degrees
deg = np.arange(0, 361, 1)
alpha = np.deg2rad(deg)

# Rotate and compute the "unexplained" variance = sum of squared y' for each angle
residual_ss = []
explained_ss = []

for a in alpha:
    ca, sa = np.cos(a), np.sin(a)
    x_rot =  ca * x + sa * y
    y_rot = -sa * x + ca * y
    residual_ss.append(np.sum(y_rot**2))   # want to MINIMIZE this
    explained_ss.append(np.sum(x_rot**2))  #  MAXIMIZE this

residual_ss = np.array(residual_ss)
explained_ss = np.array(explained_ss)

best_idx = int(np.argmin(residual_ss))
best_deg = int(deg[best_idx])
best_resid = residual_ss[best_idx]
best_explained = explained_ss[best_idx]

print(f"Best angle (min residual on y′): {best_deg}°")
print(f"Residual sum of squares at best angle: {best_resid:.3f}")
print(f"Explained sum of squares along x′ at best angle: {best_explained:.3f}")

# Polar plot of residual vs angle
fig, ax = plt.subplots(subplot_kw={'projection': 'polar'}, figsize=(6,6))
ax.plot(alpha, residual_ss)
ax.set_title("Sum of squared y′ (unexplained variance) vs angle")
ax.set_rticks([])

# Mark the best angle
ax.plot([alpha[best_idx], alpha[best_idx]], [0, residual_ss[best_idx]], linewidth=2)
plt.show()

Best angle (min residual on y′): 45°
Residual sum of squares at best angle: 17.489
Explained sum of squares along x′ at best angle: 180.511

After rotating the dataset by the best angle (~45°), we see that the data is almost completely aligned along the new x′ axis.

This confirms that x′ is the first principal component, capturing the maximum variance.

Versicolor and Virginica separate better along this axis, with Virginica having larger values and Versicolor smaller. The y′ values (residuals) are small, meaning little variance is left unexplained.

Limitations of SVD/PCA¶

It is a fair assumption to consider PCA a non normallized version of SVD (check the math) however there are other that this part of the lab shall reveal. SVD is often used to look at measured (discrete) data and extract the normalized vectors from it. Here we shall first construct known data and then try to retrieve the data in it. We use for this we construct a sequence of non overlapping spectra of different species and look at the progression of the kinetic: WE excite the ground state of the same (excitation is before the space of observation) and then see the components A, B, C decay back into the ground state
GS -> A-> B-> C -> GS

In [40]:
gauss = lambda x,mu,sigma=50: np.exp(-((x-mu)/sigma)**2)
x=np.arange(300,800,1)
spectra=pd.DataFrame({'A':gauss(x=x,mu=400),'B':gauss(x=x,mu=600),'C':gauss(x=x,mu=700),'GS':gauss(x=x,mu=500)},index=x)
spectra.index.name='wavelength in nm'
time=np.logspace(-2,4,int(1e4))
c=np.zeros((len(time),3))
rates=[1/0.1,1/10,1/1000]
c[0,0]=1
for i,t in enumerate(time[1:]):
    dc=c[i,:]
    timestep=t-time[i]
    dc[0]+=-rates[0]*timestep*dc[0]
    dc[1]+=rates[0]*timestep*dc[0]-rates[1]*timestep*dc[1]
    dc[2]+=rates[1]*timestep*dc[1]-rates[2]*timestep*dc[2]
    dc[dc<0]=0
    c[i+1,:]=dc
c=pd.DataFrame(c,index=time,columns=['A','B','C'])
c['GS']=-1*c.sum(axis=1)
c.index.name='time in ps'
data=0
for i,col in enumerate(c.columns):
    A,B=np.meshgrid(c.loc[:,col].values,spectra.loc[:,col].values)
    C=pd.DataFrame((A*B).T,index=c.index)
    if i==0: data=C
    else: data=data+C
data.columns=spectra.index.values

fig,ax=plt.subplots(1,3,figsize=(14,4))
spectra.plot(ax=ax[0])
c.plot(ax=ax[1])
ax[1].set_xscale('log')
X, Y = np.meshgrid(data.columns.values.astype(float), data.index.values.astype(float))
ax[2].pcolormesh(X,Y,data.values,cmap='jet')
ax[2].set_yscale('log')
ax[2].set_xlabel(spectra.index.name)
ax[2].set_ylabel(c.index.name)
fig.tight_layout()

Task¶

Use SVD on the DataFrame "data" just generated, plot the plot the spectra, the kinetics and the strength of the first 5 singular vectors in this data. why are they different? Any idea how you would fix that?
Hint: Check that you have the right orientation of the matrics by comparing the dimensions to the DataFrame

Data = USV^T

  • U (left singular vectors) → “kinetics-like” (time dependence).
  • V (right singular vectors) → “spectral-like” (wavelength dependence).
  • S (singular values) → strengths (importance of each component).
In [41]:
# --- Perform SVD
X = data.values
U, s, VT = np.linalg.svd(X, full_matrices=False)
V = VT.T

# limit to first 5 comps (or fewer if matrix is smaller)
ncomp = min(5, len(s))

# normalize sign so they look consistent
def norm_sign(vec):
    i = np.argmax(np.abs(vec))
    return vec if vec[i] >= 0 else -vec

U_plot = np.apply_along_axis(norm_sign, 0, U[:, :ncomp])
V_plot = np.apply_along_axis(norm_sign, 0, V[:, :ncomp])
s_plot = s[:ncomp]

# --- Plot
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(16, 4))

# Spectral shapes (V)
for k in range(ncomp):
    axes[0].plot(data.columns, V_plot[:, k], label=f"V{k+1}")
axes[0].set_title("Spectral shapes (V)")
axes[0].set_xlabel("Wavelength (nm)")
axes[0].legend(ncol=2)

# Kinetics (U)
for k in range(ncomp):
    axes[1].plot(data.index, U_plot[:, k], label=f"U{k+1}")
axes[1].set_title("Kinetics (U)")
axes[1].set_xlabel("Time (ps)")
axes[1].set_xscale("log")
axes[1].legend(ncol=2)

# Strengths (singular values)
axes[2].bar(range(1, ncomp+1), s_plot)
axes[2].set_title("Strengths")
axes[2].set_xlabel("Component")
axes[2].set_ylabel("Singular value")

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

I first generated synthetic spectral data for species A, B, C, GS with different decay kinetics.

The raw data block shows the input. The SVD block shows the decomposition.

  • Then you applied SVD/PCA to decompose the data matrix into:
  • U (time dependence → “kinetics-like”),
  • V (wavelength dependence → “spectral-like”),
  • s (singular values → “strength” of each component).

Q: Why are they different?¶

  • Because SVD is a purely mathematical decomposition.
  • It finds orthogonal basis vectors that capture variance, not the true physical spectra/kinetics.
  • The species spectra overlap, so SVD modes are linear combinations of A, B, C instead of exact recovery.

Q: Any idea how you would fix that?¶

  • We could add constraints like non-negativity (Non-negative Matrix Factorization).
  • Or use global fitting (fit the data directly to kinetic models). PCA/SVD alone cannot guarantee physically interpretable components, only variance-maximizing directions.

# ---- ADD: fill rows 2..5 with KMeans on ALL 4 features, view = petal length vs petal width
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans

k_values = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]          # columns
ninit_values = [1, 2, 5, 20]        # rows 2..5

# indices for the 2D view (petal features), so all rows are comparable to row 1
px = df_iris.columns.get_loc("petal length (cm)")
py = df_iris.columns.get_loc("petal width (cm)")

X_all = df_iris.values

for r, n_init in enumerate(ninit_values, start=1):       # rows 1..4 (indexing from 0 -> 1..4)
    for c, k in enumerate(k_values):                     # columns 0..4
        km = KMeans(n_clusters=k, n_init=n_init, random_state=12345)
        labels = km.fit_predict(X_all)
        ax[r, c].scatter(df_iris.iloc[:, px], df_iris.iloc[:, py], c=labels, s=6)
        ax[r, c].set_title(f"k={k}, n_init={n_init}")
        ax[r, c].set_xlabel("petal length (cm)")
        ax[r, c].set_ylabel("petal width (cm)")

fig.suptitle("Iris — KMeans on ALL 4 features (view: petal length vs petal width)", y=1.02)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

    ax[0, 0].scatter(df_iris.loc[mask, feat_a], df_iris.loc[mask, feat_b], s=6, label=names[i])
for j in range(5):
    if j > 0:
        for i in np.unique(selector_given):
            mask = selector_given == i
            ax[0, j].scatter(df_iris.loc[mask, feat_a], df_iris.loc[mask, feat_b], s=6, label=names[i])
    ax[0, j].set_title(f"GT  | view = {feat_a} vs {feat_b}")
    ax[0, j].set_xlabel(feat_a)
    ax[0, j].set_ylabel(feat_b)
ax[0, 0].legend(markerscale=2, fontsize=8, frameon=False)

# Rows 2..5: KMeans trained on ONLY these 2 features
for r, n_init in enumerate(ninit_values, start=1):
    for c, k in enumerate(k_values):
        km = KMeans(n_clusters=k, n_init=n_init, random_state=12345)
        labels = km.fit_predict(X_two)
        ax[r, c].scatter(df_iris[feat_a], df_iris[feat_b], c=labels, s=6)
        ax[r, c].set_title(f"k={k}, n_init={n_init}")
        ax[r, c].set_xlabel(feat_a)
        ax[r, c].set_ylabel(feat_b)

fig.suptitle(f"Iris — KMeans on ONLY 2 features ({feat_a}, {feat_b})", y=1.02)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
  • row 1 = ground-truth species (GT) in the chosen 2D view
  • rows 2–5 = KMeans with k∈{1,2,3,4,5} (columns) and n_init∈{1,2,5,20} (rows)
  • also repeated it using only two features (shows sepal length/width).

All 4 features grid:¶

  • With k=3 the clusters align best with species: setosa is clearly separated; versicolor and virginica partly overlap.
  • For k=2 the algorithm merges species;
  • for k=4–5 it splits species into subclusters.
  • Increasing n_init (1→20) stabilizes the solution and reduces odd partitions from unlucky initializations.

Only 2 features grid (sepal length & width):¶

Using only sepal length and width loses discriminatory power, so clusters are weaker and overlap more. If we switch to petal features, separation improves markedly. Overall, using all 4 features yields the most consistent clustering.

Choosing the right Clustering method¶

try to separate the domains in all the images in the subfolder "Smileys" using the clustering methods:

Kmean and spectral clustering from sklearn.cluster

The domain image is from: Gorchy - Own work, CC BY-SA 3.0, https://commons.wikimedia.org/w/index.php?curid=4459327

Hint, for real images separating the clusters using an edge detection methoids can sometimes help. Here is a simple method for edge detection using the convolution with a simple Kernel.

In [ ]:
# --- imports ----
try:
    from skimage import data, feature
except Exception:
    %pip install -q scikit-image
    from skimage import data, feature

try:
    import cv2
    HAS_CV2 = True
except Exception:
    HAS_CV2 = False

try:
    from sklearn.cluster import KMeans, SpectralClustering
except Exception:
    %pip install -q scikit-learn
    from sklearn.cluster import KMeans, SpectralClustering

# --- load example image used in the notebook text ---
coins = data.coins()

# --- edges: prefer cv2.Canny if available; fallback to skimage.feature.canny ---
if HAS_CV2:
    edges = cv2.Canny(coins, 100, 200)
else:
    # sigma≈2 gives a sensible Canny with skimage
    edges = feature.canny(coins, sigma=2)
    # cast to 0/255 so it looks similar to cv2 output when plotted
    edges = (edges * 255).astype(np.uint8)

# --- build features for clustering ---
# intensity only
X_intensity = coins.reshape(-1, 1)
# intensity + edge strength (helps separate regions)
X_int_edge = np.column_stack([coins.ravel(), edges.ravel()])

# --- run clustering (2 clusters: foreground/background) ---
km_int = KMeans(n_clusters=2, n_init=10, random_state=0).fit_predict(X_intensity)
km_ie  = KMeans(n_clusters=2, n_init=10, random_state=0).fit_predict(X_int_edge)

spec_int = SpectralClustering(
    n_clusters=2, affinity='nearest_neighbors', assign_labels='kmeans', random_state=0
).fit_predict(X_intensity)

spec_ie = SpectralClustering(
    n_clusters=2, affinity='nearest_neighbors', assign_labels='kmeans', random_state=0
).fit_predict(X_int_edge)

# reshape labels back to image
km_int_img  = km_int.reshape(coins.shape)
km_ie_img   = km_ie.reshape(coins.shape)
spec_int_img = spec_int.reshape(coins.shape)
spec_ie_img  = spec_ie.reshape(coins.shape)

# --- visualize: original, edges, and 4 segmentations ---
fig, ax = plt.subplots(2, 3, figsize=(18, 10))

ax[0,0].imshow(coins, cmap='gray');         ax[0,0].set_title("Original");                 ax[0,0].axis('off')
ax[0,1].imshow(edges, cmap='gray');         ax[0,1].set_title("Edges");                    ax[0,1].axis('off')
ax[0,2].imshow(km_int_img, cmap='gray');    ax[0,2].set_title("KMeans (intensity)");       ax[0,2].axis('off')

ax[1,0].imshow(km_ie_img, cmap='gray');     ax[1,0].set_title("KMeans (intensity + edges)"); ax[1,0].axis('off')
ax[1,1].imshow(spec_int_img, cmap='gray');  ax[1,1].set_title("Spectral (intensity)");     ax[1,1].axis('off')
ax[1,2].imshow(spec_ie_img, cmap='gray');   ax[1,2].set_title("Spectral (intensity + edges)"); ax[1,2].axis('off')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

KMeans on intensity separates coins from the background well. Adding edges as a feature causes KMeans to isolate edges as a separate cluster, which is expected. Spectral Clustering was initially noisy because the neighborhood graph was not fully connected; after scaling features and increasing the number of neighbors (or using an RBF affinity), the segmentation becomes more stable. Light Gaussian smoothing and/or adding pixel coordinates can further improve separation.
